<span class="Underline"> Distinguishing legitimate violence from terrorism prevents moral nihilism.</span>
<span class="Underline">Elshtain ‘3 (Jean Bethke, Prof. Social and Pol. Ethics – U. Chicago, “Just War Against Terror: The Burden of American Power in a Violent World”, p. 19-20)</span>
<span style="font-size: 2.66667px;">In a situation in which noncombatants are deliberately targeted and the murder of the maximum number of noncombatants is the explicit aim, using terms like "fighter" or "soldier" or "noble warrior" is not only beside the point but pernicious. Such language collapses the distance between those who plant bombs in cafes or fly civilian aircraft into office buildings and those who fight other combatants, taking the risks attendant upon military forms of fighting. There is a nihilistic edge to terrorism: It aims to destroy, most often in the service of wild and utopian goals that make no sense at all in the usual political ways. The distinction between terrorism, domestic criminality, and what we might call "normal" or "legitimate" war is vital to observe. It helps us to assess what is happening when force is used. This distinction, marked in historic moral and political discourses about war and in the norms of international law, seems lost on those who call the attacks of September 11 acts of "mass murder" rather than terrorism and an act of war under international law, and who go on to claim that the United States has also engaged in "mass murder" in its legally authorized counteroffensive that removed the Taliban and disrupted the Al Qaeda network and its terrorist training camps in Afghanistan. This argument perpetrates a moral equivalence that amounts to the "pile of garbage" that Stephen Carter noted. 15 If we could not distinguish between an accidental death resulting from a car accident and an intentional murder, our criminal justice system would fall apart. And if we cannot distinguish the killing of combatants from the intended targeting of peaceable civilians and the deliberate and indiscriminate sowing of terror among civilians, we live in a world of moral nihilism. In such a world, everything reduces to the same shade of gray and we cannot make distinctions that help us take our political and moral bearings. The victims of September 11 deserve more from us.</span>

<span class="Underline"> American intervention is legitimate. Contrary claims exaggerate civilian casualties and ignore intentionality.</span>
<span class="Underline">Elshtain, ’11 [Jean Bethke, Prof. Social and Pol. Ethics – U. Chicago. “Reply”. International Relations, March 2011, 25. http://ire.sagepub.com/content/25/1/135.citation]</span>
<span style="font-size: 5.33333px;">I would remind us once again of the context in which I wrote, one I articulated in my response to Dr O’Driscoll. I refer to a context in which there is general international consensus on a given horror, e.g. the Taliban regime, not even recognized as legitimate by the overwhelming majority of the world’s states. With reference to Afghanistan, I should hate to think that I suggest anything of the sort Professor Zehfuss taxes me with, namely, that it is ‘all right to kill a few Afghanis as they are anyway in the habit of killing each other at a much higher rate’. That is not my point. I was responding to wildly overinflated figures of civilian casualties as ‘proof positive’ that the US was somehow ‘worse’ than the Taliban, and to that end I garnered the best available data – not wild extrapolations from a few cases – in order to get the most accurate approximate reckoning of unintended civilian casualties. I cited sources that indicated that, in light of the full-scale military conflict under way, this figure, or these figures, were far below what had pertained in prior situations – and I assume the reference point is the Soviet–Afghani confl ict. So my claim had nothing to do with some notion that primitive Afghanis like to kill one another, so why worry about a few deaths. The real gravamen of Zehfuss’s case has to do with tragedy, intentionality, and the enormous difference I note between action undertaken with the intent to murder as many non-combatants, as many civilians, as possible – a 9/11 in which noncombatants are the target – and, by contrast, those situations in which civilians are not being targeted; everything possible is being done not to harm them; but some civilian casualties occur anyway. You simply cannot ‘do’ just war without observing this distinction: it is critical and a standard feature of the historic just war argument. This is not so mysterious. Intentionality is central to how we assess moral goods and harms in everyday life and in the law. An example I give is finding a body on the ground: someone lies dead on the pathway. How did he get there? Did he stumble, fall, and hit his head on a rock, in which case no one intentionally killed him? Although possibly there may be some measure of culpability if the owner of the garden where the path is found provided poor lighting (let us assume it was night) and did not clear the pathway of obstructions. If, by contrast, the victim and another person had an argument and the other person gave the victim a push, the victim stumbled, fell, and was killed as a result of the fall, we assess a higher level of culpability: manslaughter, some form of unintended killing. If, however, we turn the victim over and there is a knife stuck in his heart, we are dealing with murder and full culpability comes into view. As I said: not so mysterious and fundamental to any rule of law. Should I intentionally aim to kill as many non-combatants as possible I am culpable in a way that those who try to stop me from doing that, and wind up harming civilians unintentionally in the process, are not. The US is not blowing up mosques and markets and schools in Iraq. The US is not using children as human shields and blowing the children to smithereens as they trigger a bomb in the car in which the children have been passengers – after the adults have abandoned the vehicle. The US military brings to trial soldiers who commit crimes because these soldiers have violated rules of engagement in some egregious way by not taking suffi cient care to avoid harm to civilians or, even worse, intentionally harming civilians. Obviously there are always questions to be asked when civilians are harmed: was this the only way to get at the enemy? Was all care taken? Were the stakes so high that the risk of collateral damage was acceptable? This, it seems to me, is pretty straightforward. Not so straightforward is the matter of tragedy: ‘every civilian death is a tragedy’, I say, yes, but not every civilian death is a culpable crime, an intentional murder. In my book, I also take to task those who called 9/11 a tragedy, as if the events of that day were akin to a flood or an earthquake, and there was no human agency involved. Somehow this horrible thing just happened. There are, of course, tragedies wrought by nature in the absence of intentionality. Some terrible events are beyond human responsibility: some are and some are not. In JWAT, I clearly assign culpability: this happened. Who is responsible? What is an appropriate response to this act of war? This by contrast to calling such events a tragedy tethered to no assigning of responsibility. Tragedy goes much beyond the meaning proffered by Terry Eagleton and cited by Zehfuss, namely, that it means something ‘very sad’. Far more than that, for the sadness must be accounted for: we can be sad about a roaring fl ood that claims lives but we are both sad and mad about human actions that knowingly set out to take lives and succeed. Every unintended civilian death is a tragedy, yes. Every intentional slaughter of civilians is a crime – as well as being tragic. It is not the case that one dead body equals another. There could be no coherent rule of law were this true. Missteps when all care was taken are one thing; carelessness yet another (when more care could have been taken); aiming to maximize civilian deaths another. It is important, at all times, to keep alive the tragic dimension of war, even when justifiable, and that is why unintended civilian deaths are tragic. This does not mean, perforce, that a war has become illegitimate. If a military fighting a justified war routinely violates the rule of discrimination in the just war tradition (discriminating between civilians and combatants), this violation of jus in bello, should it be ‘normalized’, must at some point, it seems to me, raise questions about justifiability over all. But, to repeat: it is not the US slaughtering civilians in Iraq. That the US is responsible for a certain number of civilian casualties, as unintended victims of war, is certainly true. But as Prime Minister Blair and many others have argued repeatedly – in the UK, I would refer to the online journal Democratiya for further elaboration on such themes – it is the so-called ‘insurgency’ that is intentionally murdering civilians, as many as possible. It is grotesque for anyone to blame the US or Great Britain for that mordant fact. (Professor Zehfuss does not do this, let me hasten to add, but responding to her gave me an opportunity to make this point.) </span>

