<span class="Underline">We see today that the military balance in the Western Pacific is eroding in particular driven by the modernization of the PLA’s force structure and military. Right now, the Department of Defense in particular – the services are looking at the development of a new concept commonly called air-sea battle. It’s referred to in the Quadrennial Defense Review to help to arrest this decline. But my argument today is that the growing anti-access and area denial threats we face today in the Western Pacific are only the first manifestation and that what we’re going to see is we’re going to see a maturation of the anti-access capabilities and we’re going to see their proliferation coupled with the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. What I would argue is that we may in fact be entering what could be called the post-power projection era in which traditional modes of power projection may no longer be as viable as they’ve been in the recent past. This is not only going to be true at the high-end of conflict as we think on force engagements but as Peter noted, with the proliferation of both WMD and precision guided weapons, guided rockets, artillery, mortars and missiles, the kinds of capabilities we’re seeing show up in the hands of non-state actors like Hezbollah today. Countries like Iran, non-state actors, terrorist groups are acquiring the means necessary to complicate traditional power projection. What this means is it’s going to be harder for us to deploy into distant theaters against a range of potential adversaries to gain access in those theaters. It’s going to be harder for us to operate once we’re there, especially in traditional modes of operation and it’s going to be far harder to sustain logistically, with very long logistics tail stretching all the way back to the continental United States, those forward forces. CNAS published a great paper last year looking at the contested commons. And one of the things that’s really hallmark to U.S., for the U.S. military is the control of various domains, whether it’s sea control, space control, control of the air space over our force and over our allies and friends around the world, you name it.</span>

